    <section xml:id="CHANGE_ME2">  
        <info>  
            <title xml:id="CHANGE_ME2.title">Installing the &chat_client; chat client </title>          
        </info>
        <para>The &chat_client; client is available as a Docker image or as Python code available
            from GitHub. Complete of the the following procedures.</para>
            
            <procedure>
                <title>Docker procedure</title>
            <para>To prepare to use the Docker image, first install <link
                    xlink:href="https://www.docker.com">Docker</link> and <link
                    xlink:href="https://docs.docker.com/compose/">Docker Compose</link> or,
                alternatively, the drop-in daemonless Docker-equivalents <link
                    xlink:href="https://podman.io">Podman</link> and <link
                    xlink:href="https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-compose.1.html"
                    >Podman Compose</link>. We recommend using Podman because it runs by default
                without root privileges .</para>
            <step>
                <para>On Debian or Ubuntu, Podman can be installed with the following commands
                    (running as superuser). <command>Apt</command> will pull in the needed
                    dependencies.</para>
                <programlisting><prompt># </prompt><command>apt update</command>
<prompt># </prompt><command>apt install make podman podman-compose</command></programlisting>
            </step>
                <step>
                <para>Download the &chat_client; client from
                        <?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?><link
                        xlink:href="https://katzenpost.network/downloads"
                        >https://katzenpost.network/downloads</link><?oxy_custom_end?> to a
                    convenient location on your
                    computer.<?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?></para><?oxy_custom_end?>
            </step>
                <step><para>In a terminal, navigate to the directory containing the package and unzip it.</para></step>
                <step><para>In the
                    <?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?>xxx<?oxy_custom_end?>
                    directory, start the client in a container using the provided
                    Makefile.<programlisting><prompt>~$ </prompt><command>make</command></programlisting></para></step>                        
            </procedure>
        <procedure>
            <title>Python code procedure</title>
            <para>To prepare to use the &chat_client; client source code, you need Git and Python3
                installed on your Debian or Ubuntu system. Our recommended method of building the
                application is to run it in a Python virtual environment using the Makefile included
                with the code.</para>
            <step>
                <para>Install the latest Git, Python3, and Make on your
                    system.<programlisting><prompt># </prompt><command>apt update</command>
<prompt># </prompt><command>apt install git python3 make</command></programlisting></para>
            </step>
            <step>
                <para>Clone the &chat_client; repository at <link
                        xlink:href="https://github.com/katzenpost/katzenqt"/>.</para>
            </step>
            <step>
                <para>In the <filename>katzenqt</filename> directory, create a virtual environment,
                    load additional required software, and start the client using the following
                    commands.<programlisting><prompt>~$ </prompt><command>python3 -m venv myvenv</command>
<prompt>~$ </prompt><command>source myvenv/bin/activate</command>
<prompt>~$ </prompt><command>pip install --upgrade pip</command>
<prompt>~$ </prompt><command>pip install 'git+https://github.com/katzenpost/thin_client@a5f87b9623eb349ba376d7e7555c3154302216e8'</command>
<prompt>~$ </prompt><command>pip install -e .</command>
<prompt>~$ </prompt><command>make</command></programlisting></para>
            </step>
        </procedure>
