    <section>
        <title>Communicating through the &chat_client; client</title>
        <para>At first glance, &chat_client; looks much like other chat clients. It has two panes,
            one for contacts and one for messages; it has a number of modes such as chat, file
            transfer, and voice communication; and so on. </para>
        <note>
            <para>At present, only chat works.</para>
        </note>
        <para>However, this is communication tool that emphasizes anonymity, so certain procedures
            are different, and some familiar terms have slightly changed meanings. </para>
        <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
                <para>&chat_client; and &program_name; contain no information about real-world
                    identities behind contacts. There are no e-mail addresses, telephone numbers,
                    postal addresses, or anything similar involved.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
                <para>Contact display names are arbitrary.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
                <para>Contacts in one conversation are unconnected with contacts in other
                    conversations.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
                <para>Connecting with contacts requires an out-of-band (OOB) step. This is a task
                    that you and another real-world person carry out separately from &chat_client;
                    and &program_name;.</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
                <para/>
            </listitem>
        </itemizedlist>
        
        
